      "The chaotic scene at the Washington Hilton on Saturday evening, where shots fired at a security screening area sent dignitaries diving beneath banquet tables and prompted the swift evacuation of President Trump, has set off the most serious review of executive protection protocols since the assassination attempts of 2024. Federal investigators have identified the suspect as Cole Allen, a 31-year-old California resident with a background in engineering and teaching, who is scheduled to appear in federal court this week on charges that include assault on a federal officer with a dangerous weapon. Writings recovered by investigators suggest the suspect intended to target senior administration officials in attendance, a detail that has alarmed members of Congress already operating under heightened personal threat assessments. The incident marks the third time in three years that the President has been in close proximity to gunfire, raising urgent questions about whether the layered security model relied upon by the Secret Service is sufficient for the current threat environment.",
      "President Trump, who was inside the ballroom when the shots rang out, told reporters Sunday that he 'wasn't worried' during the episode, crediting the rapid response of his protective detail. Acting Attorney General Todd Blanche confirmed that the Justice Department is treating the matter as an attempted attack on federal officials and will pursue the maximum available charges. Federal prosecutors are expected to seek pretrial detention, citing the suspect's alleged communications to family members outlining his intent. The FBI's Washington Field Office is leading the investigation, with assistance from the Secret Service and the Metropolitan Police Department.",
      "Lawmakers from both parties responded with a mixture of alarm and resignation. Senate leaders on the Homeland Security Committee said they would convene closed-door briefings within the week, while several House members pointed to a steady escalation in threats directed at elected officials over the past eighteen months. The U.S. Capitol Police logged a record number of threat assessments in the previous fiscal year, a figure that has continued to climb. Several members noted that the Hilton incident exposed vulnerabilities at high-profile gatherings outside the formal Capitol perimeter, where coordination between agencies is more diffuse.",
